Simplify installation by removing composer requirement & including the vendor folder directly.

Refactored TrackerActivity and TrackgroundBackgroundActitiy.  In this version the background tracker uses a separate thread, AsyncTask, to send points to the server. The user can start the Tracker service and then navigate back to POSIT main or to other apps while it is running.  When the user restarts CoverageTracker, the View is updated by getting data from the Tracker.  Got rid of the DB tables for expeditions and expedition points on the phone.   These are not necessary.  The points are stored in an ArrayList in the TrackerState object and can retrieved whenever needed by the UI.  Also, we now use Draw to display the track on the phone -- using code that was downloaded from a nice tutorial.  The track shows as a graph of dots, connected by a line.  The size of the dots varies depending on how long the user stayed at that point.   No changes were made to the POSIT Server.

NOTE that it is still important to make sure that the location listener does not generate too many points.  This means we need a way to set the MINIMUM_DISTANCE on the fly depending on whether you're tracking a walker or cyclist or driver.

Refactored RegisterActivity, merging the RegisterUser and RegisterPhone into one activity.

Added a dialog to TrackerActivity that lets the user input the MIN_DISTANCE parameter.  Tested it with walking, cycling, and driving and it controls the number of points generated.

Revised TrackerActivity and BackgroundTrackerService  to support tracking when network service is unavailable or intermittent.

The model used is simple.  Each point received from the location service is saved to the phone's database.  It is then passed to an Async thread which handles communication with the server.  The thread sleeps -- timed wait -- while waiting for network connectivity to return.

Known issues:  The UI gets a little sluggish when too many threads are waiting because of the lack of connectivity. (Too many is 150 or so points.)   Some few points are lost if network connectivity is lost between the time a thread checks for (and finds) connectivity and the successful completion of the Http Post.

Also made changes to the Tracker interface, using buttons instead of menus.  Changes to other sources are minimal and cosmetic.

Created a TrackerSettings activity and integrated it into the Tracker making it possible now to set and change settings such as swath_width and min_recording_distance on the fly while the Tracker is running.  The Tracker settings are stored in DefaultSharedPreferences along with other POSIT settings.   The Tracker's UI is changed to include a new "Settings" button.

Implemented new Tracker functionality and fixed some minor bugs.  The Tracker is now able to save/delete, retrieve and display,  expeditions that are gathered.  None of these operations have any effect on the server.   Deletion in this case completely removes the track and all its points from the phone.  For future work, the Points table is changed to record whether or not the point has been synced with the server.

Remaining issues:
* Lost points:  points are lost when the network connection is dropped in the middle of an attempt to send a point to the server.   Additional functionality is needed to re-send such points.
* UI Response degradation: if a network outage persists for 100 points or more, UI response degrades because lots of background threads are trying to sync with the server.
* Various UI improvements can be done.  For example, the interface for the Tracker lists is very rudimentary.

Refactored and modified Tracker code to improve its over functionality and performance.  In this version points gather from the Location Listener are first saved to the Db and then sent to the server only if there is service (MOBILE or WIFI) at the time when the point is gathered.  This fixes the issue of missing points.  When the expedition is finished, any points that were not sent to the server can be synced by the user -- a button for that purpose is displayed for expeditions whose total points exceed their syced points.

Also, improved the responsiveness of the user interface (UI) by moving the Location Listener to an Async thread.  There is still room for improvement here -- possibly by a better algorithm -- but things are much improved.

This version of Tracker works even if there is no service when Tracker is started. In this case, it creates a random Expedition ID that is used during tracking.  When the completed track is later displayed, POSIT detects that it has used a random ID and syncs with the server (provided there is WIFI or MOBILE service).

This changes needs additional testing.

Known issue:  I disabled the "Notification" function in Tracker.  The problem is that when Tracker is started from the Notification status bar (after POSIT has been stopped) it makes it impossible to start PositMain, either from the Application menu or by hitting the back key when in TrackerActivity.  It seems that  when started by the Notification as  PendingIntent, TrackerActivity becomes the Main activity and thereafter it is started whenever POSIT is started -- I know that doesn't make sense but that how it seems.

Implements several revisions to the Tracker.

* Moved the registration of random-generated tracks to the foreground.  Previously it was implemented by an Async Task.   This applies to tracks generated when the phone is unable to reach a server when the expedition is started.

* Added the SYNCING_POINTS state  as a new tracker execution state -- now we have RUNNING, IDLE, VIEWING_MODE, and SYNCING_POINTS.   These states allow for different variations of the TrackerView to be displayed depending on the Tracker's execution state.  This change allows us control the UI while the points collected from random-generated tracks are being synced in a background Async thread.  The user can now navigate away from the Tracker View and, upon returning, will be show the current state of the syncing activity.   Known issue:  the syncing view does not resume updating the number of synced points when the user returns.    (Perhaps this needs some kind of activation of the view that's not being done automatically??)

* Revised the control code and fixed minor bugs in the View.  Now the tracker's current execution state is correctly reported to the user and the correct View is displayed for the execution state.

Rewrote parts of TrackerBackgroundService to improve its design and functionality.  It now uses only a single Async Task for sending points to the Posit Server.  The design is based on this nice little tutorial:  http://github.com/commonsguy/cw-android/tree/master/Service/WeatherPlus/.

Also made some minor improvements to the interface, including updating the Expedition Id immediately upon receiving it from the Server.

Known issues: there are still issues with responsiveness and with excessive garbage collection in TrackerActivity after the Trackers goes from running to idle.  These seem to be associated with the Google map.

Fixes issue #75 -- Tracker Service doesn't start on 1.5 or 1.6.  The problem was that Android Service class changed the onStart() method for versions 2.0 and higher.  It was necessary to add the old onStart() method to TrackerBackgroundService.  Now both the old method and the new method call the handleCommand(Intent) method, making the app backward compatible with 1.5 and 1.6.

Fixes issue #82 -- Tracker gets stuck in SYNCING_POINTS mode.    Following completion of the Async loop in SendExpeditionPointTask-- the loop that processes each of the unsynced points -- the Tracker state is now set to IDLE.   This means that the Tracker will be in the iDLE state even if some of the processed points were not successfully synced.
If the network connection is lost during syncing, it may be that 1 (or more??) points will be left unsynced.  This solution leaves those points to be synced (by user selection) at some later time.

One side effect of this solution:  If the network is lost while syncing unsynced points, the Tracker will remain in the SYNCING_POINTS state until the network becomes available and it can resume processing its points.   It's not clear whether this should be changed.  Perhaps a better solution might be if the network is not back up within, say, 5 minutes, the Async thread is stopped and the Tracker is put back in the IDLE state??

Add the issue and deprecated_since_version flags to all deprecation warnings

Every formal deprecation should have these two flags (though it is currently
not enforced).  Each deprecation should have an issue that tracks its
removal.  These issues should have the DeprecationRemoval tag.  The issue
should contain information to help any users who come to it with questions on
how to migrate away from the deprecated features.  The
deprecated_since_version flag will help us keep track of how long a feature
has been deprecated since.  Note that we don't as of yet have a formal policy
on when deprecated features will be removed.

Single Python 2 and 3 compatible codebase

Refactor the codebase to be both Python 2 and 3 compatable. Main changes
include:

- Absolute imports with leading `.`.

- Python 3 print function rather than print statement.

- String in Python 3 are always unicode, so unicode related functions
  have been removed.

- Integers in Python 3 are always "long", `long` methods and suffixing
  long numbers with `L` are not supported

- `map`, `filter`, and `range` return iterables rather than lists, where
  needed, wrap these calls in `list()`. As such, the Python 2 iterable
  forms of these, such as `xrange` and `ifilter`, have been removed.

- `exec` is a function rather than a statement.

- Iterators in Python 3 do not have `.next()` methods. Instead, `next()`
  can be used (Python >=2.6).

Changes related to Python 2 and 3 compatibility are in
sympy.core.compatibility.

Fix jshint errors according to new settings

Use stricter jshint settings

I added
 - unused: "vars" // warns when you define and never use your variables
 - nonbsp: true // warns about "non-breaking whitespace" characters
 - maxdepth: 8 // lets you control how nested do you want your blocks to be
 - quotmark: false // true = all quotation marks have to either be single quotes or double quotes per file
I tried to use this option with true, but I'm not sure how you like it that way. As here are quite a few use cases where single quotes would have to be escaped

I removed:
 - trailing: true // this option no longer exists in jshint
 - expr: true // this option no longer exists in jshint
 - sub: true // suppresses warnings about using [] notation when it can be expressed in dot notation: person['name'] vs. person.name

I also used maxlen: 200 for a while, but I'm not sure how the line breaks work for the docs, since I did not try that. I still think it would be a good option to use

Be aware, that a couple of options are deprecated and will be removed at some point. Instead jscs could be used to enforce styling warnings.

Part of MDL-55611

MDL-64835 JS: Stop using the jsrev in the jsrevPrefix

We only use the jsrevPrefix to determine if the cache should be
invalidated, but the prefix that we were using is based on the new
jsrev.

For example, the jsrevPrefix will be:

    hash(wwwroot + '/ + config.jsrev) + '/jsrev'

Where config.jsrev is the _current_ (new) jsrev.

As a result when searching for the jsrev used to store the data which is
currently in the storage cache, no key is returned, and we instead set
an 'initial' value and the cache is not cleared

This patch changes the jsrevPrefix to be:

    hash(wwwroot) + '/jsrev'

Since the wwwroot does not change, the key remains static for the
current site. As a result, when the jsrev is bumped via a Moodle cache
purge, we are able to correctly fetch the old jsrev from the cache,
determine that the jsrev has changed, and purge the cache.

MDL-64835 JS: Reduce cache invalidation checks

The cache invalidation check was previously occuring every time either
the `set` or `get` function was called on the cache. However, the cache
invalidation check is based on the jsrev which is static for the
lifetime of the page.

This change moved the invalidation to happen during the setup of the AMD
module such that it only happens one time per storage type (Local +
Session).

Fixing bad video player on Windows

On Windows native video player was used when user's screen was a touchscreen. I just deleted it and it solved the problem. So for everyone who had this issue, this is probably because you have a touchscreen.
Subtitles are now working fine and showing up (native video player only supports WEBVTT subtitles).

Patch for video.js to prevent mousemove spam

On certain platforms (including node-webkit on Windows7 64-bit it seems) mousemove events are spammed whether or not the mouse has actually moved. This prevents the video player UI from being hidden since it always thinks the user is moving the mouse.

This is a patch for video.js that filter out the false mousemove events. I've already sent it as a PR to the video.js people, but until they make a decision this is a stopgap measure.

I'm not sure what causes it. Someone on StackExchange said that Webkit firing phantom mousemove events might have something to do with preventing a machine going into standby. The odd thing is that it only happens when the cursor is positioned over certain content. For example, events are not fired if the cursor is positioned over the #header element when selecting a movie, but almost anywhere else will result in a constant stream of mousemoves.

The point is, this seems to fix it for now. Ideally, it should be fixed in Webkit (assuming that's where the problem is from).
